ou. From \"The Floods of 1927 in the Mississippi Basin\", Frankenfeld, H.C., 1927 Monthly Weather Review Supplement No. 29.","credit":"Archival Photography by Steve Nicklas, NOS, NGS · Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1927_Mississippi_Flood_New_Iberia.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8c/Bayou_Teche_and_Atchafalaya_River.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8c/Bayou_Teche_and_Atchafalaya_River.jpg","cap":"and Atchafalaya River","desc":"The intersection of Bayou Teche and the Wax Lake outlet of the Atachafalaya River near Patterson, Louisiana, USA. Bayou Teche runs straight up the center of the picture. The Wax Lake outlet of the Atchafalaya runs across left–right. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers has built water control structures on the bayou where it intersects with the river.","credit":"Michael Maples, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers · Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bayou_Teche_and_Atchafalaya_River.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/89/The_Fight_at_Corney%27s_Bridge.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/89/The_Fight_at_Corney%27s_Bridge.jpg","cap":"The Fight at Corney's Bridge","desc":"\"The Fight at Corney's Bridge, Bayou Teche, Louisiana, and Destruction of the Rebel Gun-boat 'Cotton,', January 14, 1863.\" Line engraving published in \"Harper's Weekly\", 1863, showing the Confederate gunboat J.A. Cotton engaging Federal gunboats, as Confederate troops fire from the shore. U.S. Navy ships in this engagement were Kinsman, Estrella, Diana and Calhoun.","credit":"U.S. Naval Historical Center Photograph. Photo #: NH 58767 · CC0","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Fight_at_Corney%27s_Bridge.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5c/Bayou_Teche_2004.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5c/Bayou_Teche_2004.jpg","cap":"2004","desc":"